(1240, 'JOUR-GA 1019', 124, 6, 'Curr Prob Mass Comm:', 'Topical issues in journalism. Subjects vary: media criticism, perspectives on race and class, global journalism, and others.', 4, '', 1, 0),
(1241, 'JOUR-GA 1022', 124, 6, 'Writing/Report Wkshp II Business and Economic Repo', 'Business and Economic Reporting Literary Reportage Magazine Reporting the Nation/Reporting New York Science , Health and Enviornmental Reporting Studio 20 Workshop I is taken the first semester; Workshop II, the second semester. Provides a foundation in the principles and practices of basic news reporting. Includes lectures on reporting principles and techniques, study of specialized areas of reporting, and completion of increasingly challenging in-class assignments. Students use New York City as a laboratory to gather and report actual news events outside the classroom. A special section of Workshop I is offered for students in the cultural reporting and criticism concentration. A special section of Workshop II is offered for students in the Business and Economic Reporting Program. ', 4, '', 1, 0),
(1242, 'JOUR-GA 1025', 124, 6, 'Issues in Online Journalism', 'Issues in Online Journalism', 4, '', 1, 0),
(1243, 'JOUR-GA 1050', 124, 6, 'Literary Journalism:', 'A course for ambitious writers who want to learn to read the way professional writers read, explicating the structure and language of well-crafted narratives and learning how to apply those lessons and techniques to their own work. Close readers and careful thinkers are wanted.', 4, '', 1, 0),
(1244, 'JOUR-GA 1070', 124, 6, 'Broadcast Writing Wkshp', 'In this class you will learn to combine the skills learned in your previous writing and reporting classes with multimedia tools including audio, video, photography, and web presentation, allowing you to explore stories beyond the boundaries of the printed page. We will cover writing for broadcast (both radio and television) as well as writing for a variety of online formats. While this course will offer some instruction in the tools and techniques of multimedia production, the main focus of the course will be on using those tools to enhance your storytelling. The emphasis will be on solid science journalism employing multimedia tools ? not just bells and whistles. You will be expected to enter this course with a basic familiarity with video production using the department''s Avid systems. We will explore techniques and tools for audio, video, and web work, with an end goal of combining all those tools to produce (in small teams) a full multimedia web package by the end of the course. ', 4, '', 1, 0),
(1245, 'JOUR-GA 1148', 124, 6, 'Visual Thinking', 'Visual Thinking', 2, '', 1, 0),
(1246, 'JOUR-GA 1171', 124, 6, 'Radio Reporting', 'Radio Reporting', 4, '', 1, 0),
(1247, 'JOUR-GA 1172', 124, 6, 'Television Reporting II', 'This intermediate second-semester course is run like a local news operation. The students work individually as reporters some weeks and as crew other weeks. They cover beats and dThis intermediate second-semester course is run like a local news operation. The students work individually as reporters some weeks and as crew other weeks. They cover beats and do short investigative and enterprise stories as well as cover breaking news and NYU-related stories that air weekly on NYU Tonight. A three-hour editorial meeting provides the time to pitch and plan stories as well as critique finished pieces. Shooting and editing are done as needed with an open schedule. Students have full access to the DV equipment and editing systems throughout the week. Students edit their in-depth pieces on the Final Cut Pro nonlinear editing system. ', 4, '', 1, 0),
(1248, 'JOUR-GA 1182', 124, 6, 'Specialized Reporting: Digital Newsroom Global Bea', 'Digital Newsroom Global Beat Investigative Reporting Longform Essay News Analysis Political Cinema Portfolio Reporting Social Worlds Studio II A variety of specialized reporting courses is offered on a rotating basis', 4, '', 1, 0),
(1249, 'JOUR-GA 1188', 124, 6, 'Environmental Reporting', 'Designed to train students to write balanced, informative articles about environmental issues and alert them to the special problems reporters face covering a beat that is often highly charged and highly politicized. For this reason, the investigative aspects of environmental reporting are emphasized.', 4, '', 1, 0),
(1250, 'JOUR-GA 1231', 124, 6, 'Magazine Writing Wkshp | Magazine Writing Wkshp: C', 'Covering the Food World Profiles Teaches the practical skills required of a nonfiction magazine writer, as well as how to focus an article for a particular market. Emphasis is on producing pieces that both inform and entertain through the careful use of language and the cultivation of an effective, powerful style. Each student writes a magazine-length article of publishable quality.', 4, '', 1, 0),
(1251, 'JOUR-GA 1281', 124, 6, 'Tpc in Cult Journalism Advanced Critical Essay Rep', 'Advanced Critical Essay Reporting the Arts Focuses on a broad cultural theme, allowing students to pursue a variety of interests. Students read and discuss relevant works of cultural journalism, explore an aspect of the topic in depth, and produce a substantial writing project.', 4, '', 1, 0),
(1252, 'JOUR-GA 1290', 124, 6, 'Fieldwork in Journalism', 'Students who have completed more than half the required courses may receive permission to intern with area publications or broadcast stations. Their work is evaluated by executives and editors of the cooperating news organizations.', 1, '', 1, 0),
