(2603, 'UPADM-GP 269', 318, 12, 'How to Change the World: Advocacy Movements in the', 'How does someone go about changing the world? What can we learn from the past about what it means to be an effective agent of change? This course will focus on several broad social movements in post-war America, including: Occupy Wall Street: the movement for African-American civil rights, including the charter school movement; the conservative movement, including the Tea Party; the Gay & Lesbian Civil Rights Movement, including AIDS activism; and the Consumer Movement including the Food Consciousness Movement. There are two objectives for this course: Ã¼ To introduce and familiarize students with these social movements that span post-war American history, putting each in its historical context; Ã¼ To use these movements to illustrate the variety of tactics and strategies employed by advocates to advance social change including demonstrations, boycotts, legislation, regulatory action, electoral politics, marches, and voter referenda. ', 4, '', 1, 0),
